    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper proposes a new mathematical framework for quantum gravity phenomenology, arguing that a known effect called \"relative locality\" \u2014 where distant observers disagree about where events occur \u2014 can arise even without the curved momentum geometry that has traditionally been thought necessary. The review board found the central conceptual idea (keeping ordinary spacetime, rather than momentum-space, as the primary arena) genuinely interesting and structurally novel. However, reviewers identified significant technical gaps in the mathematical proofs, particularly the missing construction linking momentum-space curvature to the paper's central geometric object. The paper reads as a promising but incomplete research program, with key results deferred to future work.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper introduces a fibre-bundle framework where spacetime M (not momentum-space) serves as the base manifold, defines an observer-dependent spacetime S via equivalence classes of locally measured momentum sections, and encodes deformed PQG dynamics through an Ehresmann connection H_D. The curvature-independence claim for relative locality is argued by a single flat-space free-particle example with an ad hoc constant horizontal lift, not a general proof. Three technical gaps were flagged unanimously across all reviewers and both review cycles: (1) the claimed construction from the second fundamental form II to an Ehresmann connection (Sec. 5) is not given \u2014 II is a normal-bundle-valued bilinear form and the conversion to a horizontal subbundle is missing; (2) standard causal-set axioms (local finiteness, antisymmetry, acyclicity) are not verified for S, and superluminal propagation permitted by the deformed cones can generate closed causal curves; (3) whether Assumption 2 commits a type mismatch (treating an Ehresmann connection as addable to a vector field) is disputed and depends on the PDF formula obscured by HTML rendering. The observer-independence contradiction objection raised by Gemini was rejected by Claude and partially by Codex as a mischaracterization of the paper's layered architecture."
    }
